node.text:
@dankemshunter crushing Back to Banana phenos day 49.⠀
⠀
"Light intensity:⠀
Luxx 645w LED Pro⠀
Started veg at 250ppfd. Ramped up to 400ppfd by late veg. Started flower at 600ppfd. Ramped up to 1100ppfd by day 12 of flower. Maintained that 1100ppfd until flush. Dropped light intensity down to 800ppfd for flush.⠀
⠀
Feed:⠀
@athena.ag Pro line 3EC from third fee from germination to flush.⠀
Germinated seeds with RO water. Prior to that I soaked them in 4mL per gallon Stack for 2 minutes. I planted seeds at 1EC, then quickly realized that wasn’t enough. Hit them with 2.5EC, then every feed after that was 3EC until flush in flower. Flush started with 5mL per gallon Cleanse, until I saw my runoff hit .8EC. Flush is now just straight RO"⠀
⠀
#LuxxLighting #ByGrowersForGrowers #AthenaAg

node.text:
@phatpanda @javematters Stacking the 645w LED closer than a 4x4 footprint. We haven't seen anyone running a lighting array closer than these guys, straight crush mode on Grape Cream Cake. ⠀
⠀
35 lights in this room with 13 tons of cooling and 4, 205-pint dehumidifiers.⠀
⠀
Running at 60% on the start date and transitioned to 100% within 7 days at 18” from the top of the canopy. "The largest benefit we have found was of course the increased PPFD output. This room was originally equipped with 24 1000w HPS fixtures that averaged around 600 ppfd. After the switch, our average ppfd is now around 900 and we are still saving on energy consumption. In addition to this, the finished product is simply incredible. We are seeing the same, if not better performance than our standard HPS program." - Tyler, Facilities Manager @thctech1791⠀and Mojave, AG Director @javematters 
⠀
#LuxxLighting #PhatPanda #ByGrowersForGrowers

node.text:
PPFD footprint testing is a huge part of our R&D at Luxx Lighting. We use this testing to maintain quality control and to establish benchmarks to make improvements. We test dozens of prototype fixtures, along with fixtures from most of our competitors. It starts in our testing room constructed out of DPS panels to simulate the most realistic reflectance parameters. We test in a 5.5' x 14' wide room which lets us test up to 3 lights in an array, and get a good look at overlap. We collect 33 test points on a 4' x 4' footprint and 41 test points on a 5' x 5' footprint using a Gigahertz-Optik CSS-45 meter. Testing heights range from 6" to 4'. ⠀
⠀
